{"cells":[{"source":"<a href=\"https://www.kaggle.com/code/dalmacyali1905/introduction-to-the-law-of-large-numbers?scriptVersionId=139115001\" target=\"_blank\"><img align=\"left\" alt=\"Kaggle\" title=\"Open in Kaggle\" src=\"https://kaggle.com/static/images/open-in-kaggle.svg\"></a>","metadata":{},"cell_type":"markdown"},{"cell_type":"markdown","id":"9c079a12","metadata":{"papermill":{"duration":0.0025,"end_time":"2023-08-06T20:38:41.659236","exception":false,"start_time":"2023-08-06T20:38:41.656736","status":"completed"},"tags":[]},"source":["Introduction\n","\n","The law of large numbers (LLN) is a theorem in probability theory that states that as the number of trials in an experiment approaches infinity, the average of the results will get closer and closer to the expected value. In other words, the LLN says that if you repeat an experiment a large number of times, the average of the results will be very close to the true average of the population.\n","\n","1. Flipping a coin: If you flip a coin 10 times, you might not get exactly 5 heads and 5 tails. However, if you flip a coin 1000 times, you will be very close to getting 500 heads and 500 tails. This is because the LLN states that the average of the results of flipping a coin will get closer and closer to 50% heads as the number of trials increases.\n","\n","2. Rolling a die: If you roll a die 10 times, you might not get exactly 1.5 as the average result. However, if you roll a die 1000 times, you will be very close to getting 3.5 as the average result. This is because the LLN states that the average of the results of rolling a die will get closer and closer to 3.5 as the number of trials increases.\n","\n","3. Estimating the population mean: The LLN can be used to estimate the population mean. For example, if you want to estimate the average height of all adults in the United States, you could randomly sample 1000 adults and calculate the average height of the sample. The LLN states that the average height of the sample will be very close to the average height of the population as the sample size increases.\n","\n","4. Testing statistical hypotheses: The LLN can also be used to test statistical hypotheses. For example, you could use the LLN to test the hypothesis that the average height of all adults in the United States is 5 feet 10 inches. You could randomly sample 1000 adults and calculate the average height of the sample. If the average height of the sample is significantly different from 5 feet 10 inches, then you could reject the hypothesis that the average height of the population is 5 feet 10 inches."]},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":1,"id":"5c7b76cf","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.execute_input":"2023-08-06T20:38:41.667264Z","iopub.status.busy":"2023-08-06T20:38:41.665066Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-08-06T20:38:42.341243Z","shell.execute_reply":"2023-08-06T20:38:42.338869Z"},"papermill":{"duration":0.684124,"end_time":"2023-08-06T20:38:42.345085","exception":false,"start_time":"2023-08-06T20:38:41.660961","status":"completed"},"tags":[]},"outputs":[{"data":{"image/png":"iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAA0gAAANICAIAAAByhViMAAAABmJLR0QA/wD/AP+gvaeTAAAg\nAElEQVR4nOzdd2ATZR8H8Cc76d50UUZZZZS9NwJltZQhIlCGoiBTlFemMkQERCpLBFH2VlSQ\nUpCljIIMGTLKapkt0E3bNPPePy65pGmaXrqSnN/PX5e7J8/97u65J7/c5FEURQAAAADA8fFt\nHQAAAAAAlA8kdgAAAAAcgcQOAAAAgCOQ2AEAAABwBBI7AAAAAI5AYgcAAADAEUjsAAAAADgC\niR0AAAAARyCxAwAAAOAIJHYAAAAAHIHEzoEpsk/yzBFJpH5BNbtHxyzd/IeiyBvjXlzox5RM\nVmgqIc6iczw7ph79UebZvRICMBuDI9DumP9eg+p+EqFQLHVuPf2ireOBiuW4ezTBTs2KdXu0\nWv5o+zdzonu0rxbg6ywVSp3dA6vV6xE9/Osth7I1lt4FmvtsjXH7iX3y2myxJ0d6mrS0Nc9z\nTcr81jnIpAzdAgsy48y2VT6f7+LuXbdF10kLNzwqMGwUrSqVKRPc9UhJC37HbOUmnH3ftFBJ\nWZau7DGw3ASvrkUxZaq0+rxogetLWzIFfniRb3m9MZDYcZBaqXj1POn4b9tnjukZGD7kWo6y\nHCtv37Rxo0aNGjVqFLMvqRyrLUf2HyFL97cPHLFg461Hr5QajUqR/zpPbeuIwDYqdI8mjrDL\n2H+EbFi1R79MWNcsqG7MtMW/HTv3ODUtX6FR5OekPE489tvO6aP7hdTt/vsj0zSF8c/8tcYf\nNyy8yjLCfSdSTcZ8/28my+/SKIrKy8m4e/nU2nnjGtTs+leGwqqvV6iyLx17pdgELy9+Nv2M\naYSlg8SO4z